linux-hello (1.0.5-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Add SDDM (login screen) biometric authentication support.
    libpam-linux-hello now ships hello-daemon-system.service, a minimal,
    root-owned listener started at boot with no D-Bus surface and no
    ability to enroll or delete faces (verify only) — pam_linux_hello
    connects to it (a fixed /run/hello-pam/system.socket) instead of the
    usual per-user socket when context=sddm, since no per-user session/
    daemon exists yet at the login screen. Enabled opt-in only, via
    install-pam.sh (which now also enables/disables the new service
    alongside the sddm PAM line) — never unconditionally at package
    install time, since it is a new pre-authentication-reachable root
    listener. See docs/PAM_MODULE.md for the security model and known
    limitations (accepted, not solved): a timing side-channel on
    enrollment status, home directories not yet mounted at login time,
    and systemd-homed accounts.
  * hello_daemon: extract verify_with_storage() (no behavior change for
    sudo/screenlock) so both the per-user daemon and the new SDDM
    listener share the same capture/match logic against different
    per-request storage; add FaceStorage::open_read_only() (no
    create_dir_all side effect, safe against an arbitrary, not-yet-
    authenticated user's home directory); add a cross-process camera
    flock (CameraError::Busy on contention) so the per-user daemon and
    the new listener can't silently corrupt each other's captures on a
    multi-session machine.

 -- Linux Hello Team <dev@linuxhello.local>  Mon, 06 Jul 2026 12:41:10 +0200

linux-hello (1.0.4-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Fix libpam-linux-hello installing pam_linux_hello.so to /lib/security/,
    which is not on PAM's default module search path on Debian/Ubuntu
    (/lib/<multiarch>/security/) — every packaged install shipped a module
    PAM could never load. Now installed to the correct multiarch path.
  * Add automatic PAM activation for sudo and screenlock: libpam-linux-hello
    ships a systemd timer (linux-hello-pam-autoconfigure.timer) that
    configures PAM as soon as any local user enrolls a face, with no manual
    step. Respects an explicit opt-out (install-pam.sh --remove). Does not
    touch sddm (the login screen needs a separate, future architecture
    change). See docs/PAM_MODULE.md#automatic-activation.
  * install-pam.sh: extract shared PAM-editing logic into pam-lib.sh (used
    by both the manual tool and the new automatic script), add file locking
    to avoid racing with the timer, and fall back from kde-screenlocker to
    kde for the screenlock PAM service name.
  * debian/postinst: remove the dead PAM configuration case statement
    (pam_option was hardcoded to always skip it).

 -- Linux Hello Team <dev@linuxhello.local>  Fri, 03 Jul 2026 16:08:20 +0200

